 To create a colorful and interactive website based on the provided mock-up, you can use HTML and JavaScript. Here's a simple example of how you could implement this:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>My Joke Website</title>
  <style>
    /* Add styles for the joke box */
   .joke-box {
      background-color: lightblue;
      border: 1px solid black;
      padding: 10px;
      margin: 10px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="joke-box">
    <p id="joke"></p>
    <button onclick="changeJoke()">Push to reveal punchline</button>
  </div>

  <script>
    // Define a list of jokes
    const jokes = [
      {
        setup: "Why did the tomato turn red?",
        punchline: "Because it saw the salad dressing!"
      },
      {
        setup: "Why did the scarecrow win an award?",
        punchline: "Because he was outstanding in his field!"
      },
      {
        setup: "Why did the hipster burn his tongue?",
        punchline: "He drank his coffee before it was cool!"
      }
    ];

    // Set the initial joke
    let currentJokeIndex = 0;
    document.getElementById("joke").innerHTML = jokes[currentJokeIndex].setup;

    // Function to change the joke
    function changeJoke() {
      // Increment the joke index
      currentJokeIndex++;

      // If we've reached the end of the jokes, start from the beginning
      if (currentJokeIndex === jokes.length) {
        currentJokeIndex = 0;
      }

      // Update the joke on the page
      document.getElementById("joke").innerHTML = jokes[currentJokeIndex].setup;
    }
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```
This code creates a simple HTML page with a joke box that initially displays the setup of a joke. When the user clicks the "Push to reveal punchline" button, the punchline is revealed. The jokes are stored in an array, and the `changeJoke()` function is used to cycle through the jokes when the button is clicked.
